<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Cuba </F>
<H3> <TI>   Neighborhood Assemblies Charged With Solving Problems </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Neighborhood Assemblies Charged With Solving Problems </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA1405152794 Havana PRENSA LATINA in Spanish 0140 GMT 12 May 
94 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> PA1405152794 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana PRENSA LATINA </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Havana, 11 May (PL) -- Amid the island's economic 
crisis, Cubans are looking for practical solutions to their most 
pressing problems, a subject that will be broached today in 
neighborhood assemblies in Havana. 
  Jaime Crombet, vice president of the National Assembly of 
the 
People's Government (parliament), told National Television's 
channel six that all officials who have any responsibility 
whatsoever in the social development process must attend the 
neighborhood assemblies. 
  Crombet said that "we do not want monologues or useless 
meetings" and added that the meetings to discuss daily problems 
will be attended by everyone from representatives of 
administrative organizations in each neighborhood to directors 
of schools, hospitals, clinics, and stores. 
  He admitted that things are not working the same everywhere, 
thus the government must place greater emphasis on the big 
cities to handle difficulties expeditiously. 
  The first assembly of District 40, located in the Havana 
municipality of Santa Cruz del Norte, was held today. 
Initiatives were proposed at the meeting to improve the 
community. 
  District Deputy Mario Rios commented on his experience at 
the 
assembly and said he presented problems to the community so 
solutions could be found collectively. 

</TEXT>

