<F P=100> Panama </F>
<H3> <TI>   Roundup of Economic Developments </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Roundup of Economic Developments </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA1805004094 </F>
<F P=103> PA1805004094 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
BFN 

    [Editorial Report] The following is a compilation of 
reports on economic developments monitored through 17 May. 
  Harmodio Arias, commerce and industry vice minister, 
announced yesterday that the Mexican Government decided not to 
accept Panama's latest offer for paying off this country's crude 
oil debt, which has been pending for the past five years. 
Despite the fact that an agreement was made, negotiations will 
continue, and it is expected that an understanding satisfactory 
to both parties will be reached shortly. Vice Minister Arias 
refrained from disclosing the details of Panama's offer but did 
say that the current administration would like to reach to an 
agreement before the new government is sworn in. Panama 
currently maintains a $120 million debt to Mexico for crude oil 
purchased within the framework of the San Jose Pact. This debt, 
which has been outstanding since before 1989, accumulates 
monthly interest totalling $800,000. (Panama City EL PANAMA 
AMERICA in Spanish 13 May 94 p 3A) 
  Comptroller General Jose Chen Barria disclosed that $145.3 
million in exemptions were approved during 1993 for duty-free 
imported goods, export incentives, exports of nontraditional 
goods, and taxpayers credits. Tax exemptions and customs rights 
for imports totalled $135.9 million, of which $124.1 million 
corresponds to the manufacturing sector. Exemptions within this 
sector represent 91.4 percent of total exemptions and are 
related to machinery, heavy equipment, spare parts, raw 
material, semi-processed goods, containers, and imported 
bearings. The Comptroller General indicated that, although the 
1993 figures are evidence of an 8.3 percent drop from the 1992 
level, "Panama still continues to be basically an exempt 
country." He believes that the practice should be amended in 
order to use these additional revenues in other government 
sectors. (Panama City EL PANAMA AMERICA in Spanish 10 May 94 p 
B1) 

</TEXT>

