<F P=100> Bolivia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Debt Meeting With Consultative Group Set for Nov </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Debt Meeting With Consultative Group Set for Nov </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY1905211394 Santa Cruz EL MUNDO in Spanish 13 May 94 
National Section p 2 </F>

<F P=103> PY1905211394 </F>
<F P=104>  Santa Cruz EL MUNDO </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] La Paz, 12 May (Fides News Agency) -- Bolivia will 
participate in a meeting with the Consultative Group [not 
further specified] during the first week of November. Bolivia 
will participate in a meeting with the Paris Club in October to 
reschedule the bilateral foreign debt. 
  The dates were confirmed by Finance Minister Fernando 
Cossio, 
who also confirmed a meeting with the IMF for late May to reach 
a new agreement on structural adjustment. 
  Bolivia seeks financing from the Consultative Group. In 
1993, Bolivia received commitments for more than $1 billion over 
a four-year period. This year, Bolivia will go to this 
international forum to renew this financial support. 
  Cossio said the government's economic team is preparing a 
strategy to negotiate with the IMF. The new agreement with the 
IMF will be in effect for three years and include the main 
structural reform programs the current administration has in 
mind. 
  The finance minister mentioned that basically the 
capitalization's and the popular participation's impact on the 
fiscal program would be included in the agreement. 
  The minister said it is too early to discuss the amount that 
might be agreed upon with the IMF. He added that the amount 
required by our national economy would be negotiated with the 
IMF. 
  Nevertheless, it is necessary to emphasize that this 
involves 
a grants-in-aid program, including a 10-year repayment period, a 
10-year grace period, and a 0.5 percent interest rate. 

</TEXT>

