<F P=100> Uruguay </F>
<H3> <TI>   Roundup of Economic Reports </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Roundup of Economic Reports </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY1905174194 </F>
<F P=103> PY1905174194 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
BFN 

    [Editorial Report] The following is a compilation of 
reports on economic activities monitored through 19 May. 
  The National Statistics Institute has reported that the 
Consumer Price Index increased by 3.52 percent in April. The 
accrued inflation in the first quarter of the year added up to 
11.65 percent as compared with 16.1 percent in the corresponding 
period in 1993. Food and beverages, transportation, and 
communications registered the highest price increases. 
(Montevideo EL OBSERVADOR ECONOMICO in Spanish 3 May 94 p 8) 
  The trade deficit continued its upward trend in February, 
reaching $51.8 million. Exports grew by 6.5 percent while 
imports increased by nearly 17 percent in the first two months 
of 1994, resulting in a $122.3 million deficit. The reasons 
behind the trade deficit are: lack of competitiveness, the 
increase in salaries, the cost of living, the decline in the 
price of some products on the international market, and the 
reduction of tariffs that spurred purchases of imported goods. 
(Montevideo EL OBSERVADOR ECONOMICO in Spanish 4 May 94 p 9) 
  The Central Bank's net international reserves increased by 
$2.3 million in April, totaling $1.2587 billion. International 
reserves have increased by $56.8 million so far this year. The 
monetary base shrunk by $201.5 million last month due to a 
$208.8 million drop in the net domestic credit granted by the 
Central Bank. (Montevideo EL PAIS in Spanish 5 May 94 Market 
Indicators Section p 1) 
  Despite the fact that Uruguayan exports to Common Market of 
the South, Mercosur, member countries increased by 25.1 percent 
in the first two months of the year, its trade deficit with 
these countries added up to $78.7 million, thus registering a 
43.1 percent increase compared with the corresponding period in 
1993. There is a trade deficit of $48.3 million with Brazil and 
a deficit of $32.7 million with Argentina, while the surplus 
with Paraguay amounts to $2.3 million. (Montevideo EL PAIS in 
Spanish 5 May 94 Market Indicators Section p 1) 
  According to figures released by the Central Bank, Uruguay 
grew by an average 3.3 percent per annum in the four years of 
the Blanco Party administration. (Montevideo EL OBSERVADOR 
ECONOMICO in Spanish 6 May 94 p 10) 
  The State Board of Sanitation chairman has reported that 
public water rates increased by 11 percent as of 1 May. 
(Montevideo EL OBSERVADOR ECONOMICO in Spanish 6 May 94 p 10) 
  The Central Bank has reported that the public 
sector--including government-owned enterprises, town halls, and 
other decentralized agencies--registered a $9.1 million deficit 
in January 1994 despite the central government's $6.9 million 
surplus. The financial position of the public sector has been 
deteriorating since last year, when after recording a $51 
million surplus in the first quarter, it showed a deficit 
amounting to 1.5 percent of GDP by the end of the year. 
(Montevideo EL OBSERVADOR ECONOMICO in Spanish 9 May 94 p 11) 
  According to data released by the Central Bank, private 
consumption in Uruguay grew by 25.7 percent from 1990 to 1993. 
(Montevideo EL OBSERVADOR ECONOMICO in Spanish 10 May 94 p 8) 
  The Central Bank reported on 9 May that the central 
government registered a $12.6 million surplus in March. The 
accrued government surplus in the first quarter of the year 
totals $29.2 million. Despite these positive economic 
indicators, the government's accounts continued to deteriorate 
in the first quarter of the year, as revenues grew by 1.9 
percent while expenditures increased by 11.6 percent. 
(Montevideo EL OBSERVADOR ECONOMICO in Spanish 10 May 94 p 8) 
  Basing its information on data released by the Central Bank 
and the IMF, the Finance Ministry disclosed on 10 May that 
imports of capital goods have grown by 121 percent over the last 
four years. Purchases of capital goods, however, declined by 2.7 
percent in the first two months of the year as compared with the 
corresponding period in 1993. (Montevideo EL OBSERVADOR 
ECONOMICO in Spanish 11 May 94 p 9) 
  Uruguay's net external debt has dropped by 27 percent over 
the last four years due to a 47 percent increase in net 
international reserves. The per capita debt has declined from 
$1,021 to $753 over the last four years. Nevertheless, the total 
gross external debt has increased by 12.9 percent in the period 
under consideration. It amounted to $7.89 billion at the end of 
1993, thus representing 57 percent of GDP. The net external debt 
totals $2.373 billion. (Montevideo EL OBSERVADOR ECONOMICO in 
Spanish 11 May 94 p 9) 
  The Central Bank has reported that investments in fixed 
capital grew by 11.8 percent in 1993 while private consumption 
increased by 4 percent. This led to a 5.5 percent expansion in 
domestic demand. (Montevideo BUSQUEDA in Spanish 12 May 94 p 26) 

</TEXT>

