<F P=100> Inter-Caribbean Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Caricom Countries Differ Over NAFTA Participation </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Caricom Countries Differ Over NAFTA Participation </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   FL1905220594 Castries HTS Caribvision Television in English 
1945 GMT 19 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> FL1905220594 </F>
<F P=104>  Castries HTS Caribvision Television </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] More questions than answers remain as the region 
continues to discuss the controversial NAFTA accord. The latest 
voice in what is proving to be a series of never-ending debates 
is that of David Thompson. Thompson, the finance minister in 
Barbados, says the region cannot afford to sit on the edge of 
all that is happening. 
  NAFTA is a joint trade agreement signed last year between 
the 
United States, Mexico, and Canada. The big debate in Barbados 
and the region is how the grouping will respond to NAFTA. There 
already seems to be a split within Caricom [Caribbean Common 
Market] circles as to whether or not the grouping should proceed 
to enter NAFTA as a unit or to allow individual countries 
desirous of doing so to be approved to proceed. 

</TEXT>

