<F P=100> CARIBBEAN </F>
<F P=101> Cuba </F>
<H3> <TI>   Dominican Party, Candidate Claim Haitians Voted in Election </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Dominican Party, Candidate Claim Haitians Voted in Election </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   FL1905205294 Havana Radio Reloj Network in Spanish 1930 GMT 
19 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> FL1905205294 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana Radio Reloj Network </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Political sources report that the crisis, unleashed 
in the Dominican Republic in the wake of general elections 
Monday, 16 May, which are considered fraudulent by the 
opposition, has begun to escalate. 
  The Central Electoral Board's [JEC] credibility was once 
again contested when candidate for senator (Ministro Castillo), 
of the Dominican Liberation Party [PLD] led by Juan Bosch, the 
third political force in the country, announced that he was 
considering the possibility of rejecting the elections because 
some 300,000 Haitians had reportedly voted in them. 
  The elections were also protested yesterday by the 
opposition 
Dominican Revolutionary Party, which accused the JEC and two JEC 
justices of planning a fraud. 
  Moreover, the JEC decided to recount the votes one by one, 
beginning today, and to stop the release of bulletins with 
election results. 

</TEXT>

