<F P=100> Uruguay </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Minister Denies Aid Planned for Haiti </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Foreign Minister Denies Aid Planned for Haiti </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY2005023394 Madrid EFE in Spanish 0140 GMT 20 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> PY2005023394 </F>
<F P=104>  Madrid EFE </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Montevideo, 19 May (EFE) -- Uruguayan Foreign 
Minister Sergio Abreu today denied that his country will 
participate in an eventual American force that will take action 
in Haiti, and he ratified that his country does not support an 
armed intervention in that Caribbean country. 
  Abreu made his country's position known after some foreign 
media asserted that only Argentina and Uruguay were willing to 
participate in a multinational force in Haiti. 
  The U.S. State Department asked the opinion of several OAS 
member countries on the creation of a multinational force to 
dislodge the military in power in Haiti. 
  The majority of Latin American countries opposes this idea, 
which is one of three being studied in Washington. The other 
ideas include direct intervention by the United States and the 
creation of a force made up of Haitian refugees. 
  Uruguay has promoted political actions in the OAS in order 
to 
prevent the Haitian crisis from turning into a military solution. 
  Abreu stated that the country's position has not changed and 
it will work with "preventive diplomacy." 
  The foreign minister said Uruguay "is a jealous defender of 
nonintervention and the self-determination of nations." 
  "Uruguay will support all solutions that come within the 
framework of international law and the responsible 
organizations," Abreu reiterated. "The principles of 
nonintervention and self-determination are not negotiable," he 
stressed. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

