<H3> <TI>   Jose Marti Electric Plant Resumes Operation </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Jose Marti Electric Plant Resumes Operation </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   FL2005143394 Havana Radio Rebelde Network in Spanish 1100 
GMT 20 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> FL2005143394 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana Radio Rebelde Network </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["Text" of article published in 20 May issue of GRANMA </F>
newspaper -- read by announcer] 
  [Text] The Jose Marti Electric Plant in Matanzas has 
rejoined the National Electric System following a 88-day 
maintenance and calibration program. The plant generator is 
producing over 31 megawatts, near its top performance capacity. 
Chief Engineer Fermin Infante stated the generator is still 
undergoing tests without interrupting the electricity generation 
which, as we know, is attained by burning Cuban oil. 
  To give an idea of the significance of using Cuban oil, all 
that is needed is to mention that from 1986 to date, this 
35-megawatt unit has used almost 500,000 tons of oil which 
represents a saving of $22 million. The Jose Marti Plant will 
deliver an average of 19,000 megawatts a month and soon will be 
testing the Varamulsion mix, a higher quality fuel mixture 
containing Cuban oil. 

</TEXT>

