<H3> <TI>   Alarcon To Leave for London; Notes Miami Summit </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Alarcon To Leave for London; Notes Miami Summit </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   FL2105021294 Havana Radio Rebelde Network in Spanish 2300 
GMT 20 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> FL2105021294 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana Radio Rebelde Network </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Ricardo Alarcon de Quesada, president of the 
National Assembly of the People's Government [ANPP], today 
termed the U.S.-sponsored summit slated for December 1994 in 
Miami, Florida, a blow against the Ibero-American integration 
movement. 
  In remarks to PRENSA LATINA, Alarcon said that in view of 
this reality, the Ibero-American countries, the presidents of 
which will meet in the Colombian town of Cartagena de Indias in 
June 1994, will have to make a clear commitment to strengthen 
such an integrationist movement. 
  Alarcon added that if a specific program of Latin American 
and Caribbean integration is achieved, and if progress is 
achieved toward that objective, those invited will go to the 
Miami conference with the assurance of being a strong group in 
an unprecedented case of Ibero-American relationship. 
  Alarcon added that the fourth Ibero-American summit will 
become a moment of reaffirmation and consolidation of the 
movement it represents. He also referred to the Cuban exclusion 
from the invitations extended by the United States for the Miami 
summit, and called it an attempt to return international reality 
to the situation that prevailed 20 years ago. 
  Alarcon will leave tomorrow, 21 May, for London to comply 
with an official invitation extended by the two chambers of the 
British Parliament. He will stay one week in the UK. 

</TEXT>

