<H3> <TI>   Vigil Against Embargo Organized </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Vigil Against Embargo Organized </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA2305014894 Hamburg DPA in Spanish 2348 GMT 22 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA2305014894 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Port-au-Prince, 22 May (DPA) -- More than 1,000 
Haitians gathered today in a vigil, rejecting the new economic 
and commercial embargo, almost a total embargo, imposed against 
the ruling military in Haiti. 
  The demonstrators, who termed the event a nonpartisan show 
of 
patriotism, were flanked by military security patrols, a safety 
measure never before offered to exiled President Jean-Bertrand 
Aristide's supporters. 
  A witness said the demonstrators shouted chants against 
foreigners. The chants are evidence of an increasing negative 
sentiment against foreigners, confirmed by several expatriates 
as the deadline for the enforcement of the new measures 
approaches. Several foreign news teams had reportedly been 
arrested and detained for a few hours by the Haitian police in 
recent days. 

</TEXT>

