<H3> <TI>   Montreal Journalist Accepts Foreign Minister Post </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Montreal Journalist Accepts Foreign Minister Post </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   FL2005193494 Port-au-Prince Radio Tropic FM in French 1600 
GMT 19 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> FL2005193494 </F>
<F P=104>  Port-au-Prince Radio Tropic FM </F>
<F P=105>  French </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Let us point out that the new, unofficial minister 
of foreign affairs, attorney... [pauses] Mr. Charles David, who 
was appointed this week by the military regime in 
Port-au-Prince, has refused to resign from his post as 
journalist of the daily LA PRESSE in Montreal, according to the 
newspaper's management. 
  The appointment of Mr. David, 53, to a government not 
recognized by Ottawa, has led the Canadian Government to freeze 
his Canadian assets. LA PRESSE, which has employed him for 22 
years as journalist in charge of international issues, cannot 
dismiss him for the moment. Under the provisions of the 
newspaper's collective convention, he obtained a six-month leave 
without pay so he could devote himself to his political 
activities. The LA PRESSE management advises that if David 
returns to the newspaper before the expiration of the six-month 
period, he can no longer work in international service. After 
this period, he will lose his job. 
  In an editorial published on 18 May, LA PRESSE condemned the 
unofficial government in power in Port-au-Prince, which it 
labels illegitimate, unelected, and antidemocratic; and 
disapproves of Charles David's decision to be a part of it. 

</TEXT>

