<H3> <TI>   Government Wants U.S. To Lift Travel Warning </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Government Wants U.S. To Lift Travel Warning </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA2005193994 Guatemala City SIGLO VEINTIUNO in Spanish 19 
May 94 p 3 </F>

<F P=103> PA2005193994 </F>
<F P=104>  Guatemala City SIGLO VEINTIUNO </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Carlos Castanaza Rosales] </F>
  [Excerpt] Guatemalan Foreign Minister Maritza Ruiz de 
Vielman said yesterday that the Guatemalan Government is trying 
to persuade the U.S. Government to eliminate the travel warning 
that has decreased the flow of tourists to Guatemala. 
  She denied that the Guatemalan Government is not doing 
anything about the situation and said that efforts have been 
made both in Washington and at the U.S. Embassy in Guatemala. 
  The minister said the interested parties should be aware 
that 
this warning is not aimed at Guatemala alone, but that such 
directives generally include several countries. That is why the 
Guatemalan Government has presented the necessary social and 
economic arguments for a favorable resolution, although this 
warning is a unilateral U.S. decision. 
  She said the hunger strike declared by a U.S. citizen in 
front of the U.S. Embassy in Guatemala City is something that 
Washington should take into consideration when a new decision is 
made. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

