<F P=100> Honduras </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Endorses Multinational Force in Haiti </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Government Endorses Multinational Force in Haiti </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA2105210894 Paris AFP in Spanish 2004 GMT 21 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA2105210894 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tegucigalpa, 21 May (AFP) -- Honduras is willing to 
contribute to a multinational military force to restore 
democracy in Haiti, said Honduran Foreign Minister Ernesto Paz 
Aguilar on Saturday. 
  "The Honduran position has always been to unconditionally 
support the reinstatement of democracy in Haiti, a brother 
country which suffers an ignominious military dictatorship," Paz 
stated when recalling the military coup perpetrated against the 
Caribbean island's president, Jean-Bertrand Aristide, on 30 
September 1991. 
  During an interview with a local radio station, Paz said 
eventual Honduran participation in a multinational military 
force would have to occur within the framework of UN or OAS 
peace-keeping operations. 
  The foreign minister said, "Honduras is currently 
participating in a similar operation in the Western Sahara" at 
the request of the UN. 
  The head of Honduran foreign affairs emphasized Honduras has 
been "firm and categorical" when defending democracy in Haiti 
and in all countries where human rights are being violated. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

