<F P=100> Peru </F>
<H3> <TI>   Roundup of Economic Reports </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Roundup of Economic Reports </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY1905142394 </F>
<F P=103> PY1905142394 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
BFN 

    [Editorial Report] The following is a compilation of 
reports on economic activities monitored through 19 May. 
  The State Petroleum Agency has hit a production record with 
the exploitation of well 148-D in the Vivian oilfield in the 
northern jungle. Its initial production totals 6,728 barrels per 
day. The exploitation of wells 148-D and 147-D produces 35,118 
barrels per day, the highest in the past 10 years. (Lima EXPRESO 
in Spanish 7 May 94 p A22) 
  The National Mining Association, SNM, reported that mining 
exports dropped 13 percent in 1993. Lead production, however, 
rose 12 percent; zinc 10.26 percent; silver 2.7 percent; and 
iron 84 percent, when compared with 1992. Gold production 
increased 36 percent with the exploitation of the Yanacocha 
mine. (Lima EL COMERCIO in Spanish 9 May 94 Economic Section p 
B11) 
  The SNM reported that the mining industry accounted for 36 
percent of foreign investments in 1993. The National Commission 
for Foreign Investment and Technology reported that foreign 
capital totalled $1.608 billion through February 1994. (Lima EL 
COMERCIO in Spanish 9 May 94 Economic Section p B11) 
  On 10 May, Ricardo Marcenaro Frers, Democratic Constituent 
Congress Labor Committee coordinator, reported that 77.4 percent 
of the economically active population was underemployed in 1993; 
and unemployment and employment rates were 9.9 percent and 12.7 
percent respectively. (Lima EL COMERCIO in Spanish 11 May 94 p 
A4) 
  On 11 March, the international financing community decided 
to 
grant a $1.1 billion loan to Peru during the 1994-95 fiscal year 
running from July 1994 to June 1995. In face of the good results 
obtained by the Peruvian Government's economic program, 
approximately 20 countries and financial institutions agreed to 
help Peru during the meeting of the Peruvian Consultative Group 
sponsored by the World Bank in Paris. (Lima LA REPUBLICA in 
Spanish 12 May 94 Political Section p 2) 

</TEXT>

