<F P=100> Mexico </F>
<H3> <TI>   PRD Leader Attributes Problems to Party President </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    PRD Leader Attributes Problems to Party President </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA2105200894 Mexico City Radio ACIR Network in Spanish 0000 
GMT 20 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA2105200894 </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City Radio ACIR Network </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "ACIR Radio News" newscast] </F>
  [Text] Leaders of the Democratic Revolution Party [PRD], 
grouped in the National Executive Committee, are meeting in 
total secrecy at party headquarters on 50 Monterrey Street, Roma 
Neighborhood, in Mexico City. The meeting is trying to 
establish a new alliance among all the party's factions, since 
the fissure in unity is threatening even the presidential 
candidacy of Cuauhtemoc Cardenas Solorzano. We will be in 
direct contact with our colleague Maria Martinez de la Vega from 
PRD offices for all the details on this meeting. 
  As Heberto Castillo said this morning, the PRD urgently 
needs 
to make a clean sweep of procedures, not people. Speaking this 
morning to ACIR, Heberto Castillo said the problem inside his 
party is not [as heard] that PRD President Porfirio Munoz Ledo 
has lacked the discipline to heed the mandate of the National 
Executive Committee. 
  [Begin Castillo recording] What we have here is a problem 
that arose because of Mr. Porfirio Munoz Ledo's disrespect for 
the decisions of the National Executive Committee. In the 
political reforms, a plan submitted to the Government 
Secretariat and voted on, but the vote [words indistinct] even 
comrade Cuauhtemoc Cardenas. He had to distance himself from 
that position in his 18 March speech at the Zocalo. The 
fundamental difference is that we, as the PRD, have proposed 
that electoral authorities be independent of the executive 
branch. The political reforms retain the government secretary 
as chairman. [end recording] 
  As Heberto Castillo reiterated, the problem within the PRD 
is 
the indiscipline of Porfirio Munoz Ledo. 
  This morning, we interviewed PRD presidential candidate 
Cardenas. A little more at ease, Cardenas said the problems 
within his party are normal for a democratic institution that 
does not hide its differences. 
  [Begin Cardenas recording] I see no major problem. I believe 
this a normal arrangement in a party where we openly and 
publicly hold our discussions. We do not resolve our problems 
behind closed doors, but in public. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

