<F P=100> CARIBBEAN </F>
<F P=101> Cuba </F>
<H3> <TI>   Radio Notes U.S.-Sponsored Embargo on Haiti </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Radio Notes U.S.-Sponsored Embargo on Haiti </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA2205174594 Havana Radio Havana Cuba in Spanish 1300 GMT 22 
May 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA2205174594 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana Radio Havana Cuba </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Morning Information Review" newscast] </F>
  [Text] On this Sunday morning, the total UN trade embargo 
against Haiti sponsored by the United States went into effect. 
This is an attempt to pressure the Haitian military coupists 
into giving up power. 
  The sanctions include intensifying the embargo on crude oil 
and military products and equipment, in addition to an 
interdiction on all financial and commercial transactions with 
the Haitian military regime. 
  According to some observers, the embargo, to which the UN 
Security Council agreed on 6 May, could have disastrous 
consequences not only for the country's economy but also for the 
Haitian people. 
  Politicians and journalists in several countries continue to 
ponder how much longer the United States will be able to wait 
before it resorts to any pretext in order to justify a military 
invasion. Meanwhile, U.S. President William Clinton has signed 
an order barring all U.S. corporations from any type of 
commercial transactions with Haiti. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

