<F P=100> Honduras </F>
<H3> <TI>   President Says Gore's Visit Recognizes Democratic Efforts </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    President Says Gore's Visit Recognizes Democratic Efforts </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA2105025394 Paris AFP in Spanish 0017 GMT 21 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA2105025394 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tegucigalpa, 20 May (AFP) -- Honduran President 
Carlos Roberto Reina today said U.S. Vice President Al Gore's 
visit to Honduras on 24 May "is in recognition of the 
democratizing efforts" the country has made. 
  Reina added that Gore's trip to Tegucigalpa to meet with 
Central American presidents "is not by chance, because Costa 
Rica used to be the favorite nation; it is a message of 
recognition for the type of government Honduras has by popular 
mandate." 
  The Honduran president told journalists that such issues as 
the environment, human rights, corruption, foreign debt, and 
sustainable development with a "human face" are included in the 
summit agenda. 
  According to Reina, the objective of this meeting is to 
define the course the presidents will follow during the 14 June 
Ibero-American Summit in Cartagena, Colombia, and the December 
Americas Summit in Miami. 
  Presidents Ramiro De Leon Carpio (Guatemala), Alfredo 
Cristiani (El Salvador), Jose Maria Figueres (Costa Rica), 
Guillermo Endara (Panama), Violeta Chamorro (Nicaragua), and 
Belizean Prime Minister Manuel Esquivel were invited to the 
meeting. 
  A Foreign Affairs Ministry communique states that the 
Central 
American presidents will arrive in Tegucigalpa on 23 May to meet 
on that day "as a prelude to the U.S. vice president's arrival." 
  According to the Foreign Ministry, Central American experts 
will meet on 21 May to draft a common agenda to follow during 
the summits. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

