<F P=100> Colombia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Opposes U.S. Intervention In Haiti </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Government Opposes U.S. Intervention In Haiti </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA2005211494 Madrid EFE in Spanish 2002 GMT 20 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA2005211494 </F>
<F P=104>  Madrid EFE </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Santa Fe de Bogota, 20 May (EFE) -- It was announced 
today in this capital that the Colombian Government is opposed 
to possible U.S. military intervention in Haiti to depose 
provisional President Emile Jonassaint and to hand over power to 
Jean-Bertrand Aristide. 
  Colombian Foreign Ministry sources, quoted by Emisoras 
Caracol Network, said that the Colombian ambassador to the OAS, 
former Foreign Minister Julio Londono, has arrived in Santa Fe 
de Bogota for consultations with the government of President 
Cesar Gaviria on the issue of U.S. intervention in Haiti. 
  The sources said that the official Colombian position will 
be 
stated on 6 June in Belem, Brazil, during the annual OAS 
assembly, which will be attended by the foreign ministers of OAS 
member countries. The Colombian Foreign Ministry last week 
rejected the designation of Jonassaint and stated that the only 
legitimate administration in Haiti is that of Aristide, who was 
democratically elected in 1991. 

</TEXT>

