<F P=100> INTER-AMERICAN AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Andean Textile Companies Disagree on Asian Imports </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Andean Textile Companies Disagree on Asian Imports </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY2105000994 Madrid EFE in Spanish 1657 GMT 20 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> PY2105000994 </F>
<F P=104>  Madrid EFE </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Lima, 20 May (EFE) -- Business people from the 
Andean Group (Bolivia, Colombia, Ecuador, Peru, and Venezuela) 
garment industry and textile companies disagree over the textile 
industry's request to restrict Asian clothing imports. 
  The Andean Textile Federation proposed the establishment of 
minimum quotas and prices to the Cartagena Agreement Board 
(Junac) to restrict Asian textile imports that enter the region 
with undervalued prices. The Andean Garment Federation openly 
opposes that proposal because it believes the free market "is 
enough to face the unfair competition." 
  The garment industry also believes the quota system "is 
self-defeating because just as quotas would be imposed on Asian 
products, quotas could also be imposed on buying raw material in 
those countries and that would hurt us." 
  An organization spokesman said Junac experts, who apparently 
will meet in Lima today to discuss the issue, will resolve the 
disagreement as a last resort. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

