<F P=101> CUBA </F>
<H3> <TI>   TRABAJADORES Criticizes Clinton Statements </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    TRABAJADORES Criticizes Clinton Statements </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   FL2405000194 Havana Radio Rebelde Network in Spanish 1700 
GMT 23 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> FL2405000194 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana Radio Rebelde Network </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Today, TRABAJADORES published an article criticizing 
statements on Cuba by U.S. President William Clinton. In his 
article, reporter and analyst Nicanor Leon Cotallo points out 
that Clinton's recent statements on Cuba are part of the 
strategy suggested by his advisers to obtain an electoral 
victory in the State of Florida. Leon goes on to say that 
Clinton's 20 May attacks on the Cuban Government demonstrate 
that obtaining a victory in that state during the 1996 elections 
has become an obsession for the president's team of advisers. 
  In his article, Leon states that this goes hand in hand with 
the viewpoint of the most extreme right and the intolerant 
factions of the Cuban community in Florida. Leon goes on to say 
that even though Clinton is not part of the extreme right, as 
his successors Ronald Reagan and George Bush were, he must know 
very little about Cuba, the only explanation for his error, or 
lack of precision in talking about a long history of cooperation 
and mutual admiration between Cuba and the United States. 
  Regarding Clinton's defense of the blockade against Cuba, 
the 
article in TRABAJADORES states that this contradicts the 
agreements of the UN General Assembly and the opinion of the 
principal U.S. newspapers. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

