<F P=100> CARIBBEAN </F>
<F P=101> CUBA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Alarcon Interviewed Before Leaving for England </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Alarcon Interviewed Before Leaving for England </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   FL2405014794 Havana Radio Rebelde Network in Spanish 2300 
GMT 23 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> FL2405014794 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana Radio Rebelde Network </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Ricardo Alarcon de Quesada, president of the 
National Assembly of the People's Government [ANPP], said Cuba 
seeks, through the peoples' parliaments, participation of the 
entire population in the making of national decisions. In an 
interview granted to PRENSA LATINA, prior to departing for 
England on an official visit, the president of the ANPP harshly 
criticized what he called the fiction by the so-called 
representative democracies. Alarcon said such representation is 
limited to the electoral act, and that from that moment on, 
there is no relationship between the citizen who voted and the 
politician. National sovereignty is therefore limited to one day 
every few years. 
  Alarcon also referred to the experience gained by Cuba 
during 
the recent process, prior to the adoption of diverse measures to 
restructure the economy and the battle against illegal profit, 
preceded by celebration by more than 80,000 assemblies at work 
centers. 
  In discussing future participation of the ANPP in the 
application of the accorded measures, Alarcon said the ANPP is 
responsible for control of the practical application of those 
measures in a way never achieved by similar bodies in other 
political systems. Alarcon went on to say: We will control and 
oversee application of the national budget through the direct 
work of each entity or province in coordination with 
administrative authorities exchanging ideas for the reduction of 
subsidies and the increase of state income. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

