<F P=100> Dominican Republic </F>
<F P=101> Haiti </F>
<H3> <TI>   Soldiers Arrest 50 People Fleeing to U.S. </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Soldiers Arrest 50 People Fleeing to U.S. </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA2405010394 Hamburg DPA in Spanish 0012 GMT 24 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA2405010394 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Port-au-Prince, 23 May (DPA) -- Fifty Haitians 
traveling on a boat to the United States were arrested by Haiian 
soldiers today. It is the first clear sign of the new plan 
backed by the military leadership to severely punish illegal 
immigration. 
  The frustrated refugees were arrested on a beach near Petit 
Goave, a small port city located some 60 km west of 
Port-au-Prince, two independent radio stations reported in the 
Haitian capital. 
  Emile Jonassaint, the provisional president appointed by the 
Haitian military leadership, following his installation in power 
two weeks ago, warned that he would punish anyone caught 
violating the island's laws, especially the law condemning those 
who leave the country without visas or proper documents. 
  Several analysts said the Army and other enemies of exiled 
President Jean-Bertrand Aristide hope to reduce the escape of 
Haitians to prevent the United States from deciding to use its 
military strength to resolve the political crisis in Haiti, 
which has lasted 30 months. 
  Preventing the entrance of Haitian refugees has been one of 
the primary objectives of U.S. policy since the bloody military 
coup that overthrew Aristide in 1991. 
  Since the coup more than 40,000 persons have fled Haiti in 
boats. Since President Bill Clinton announced two weeks ago that 
his country would give Haitians the possibility of requesting 
political asylum instead of returning them to the island, more 
than 1,200 persons have been caught at sea and sent back to the 
Caribbean nation. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

