<H3> <TI>   Presumed Aristide Followers Killed in Cite Soleil </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Presumed Aristide Followers Killed in Cite Soleil </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA2305224494 Paris AFP in Spanish 2050 GMT 23 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA2305224494 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Port-au-Prince, 23 May (AFP) -- According to 
eyewitnesses, the bodies of four youths gunned down yesterday 
evening were found this morning in Cite Soleil, the largest 
low-income neighborhood in northern Port-au-Prince. 
  According to some residents, those murdered were followers 
of 
President-in-exile Jean-Bertrand Aristide. They reportedly were 
killed shortly before dawn by a group of unidentified armed men. 
  Since the toppling of President Aristide on 30 September 
1991, Cite Soleil has been the site of numerous acts of violence 
aimed at his followers. 
  It was also reported today that 278 "boat people" (fragile 
vessels packed with Haitian refugees) were intercepted on the 
high seas as they were trying to reach Florida. They were 
escorted back to Port-au-Prince by U.S. coast guard vessels. 
  Meanwhile, a Haitian business organization, the Center of 
Free Enteprise and Democracy (the equivalent of the young 
economic chambers), denounced today the "immorality" of UN a 
resolution reinstating a nearly full embargo against Haiti and 
the "inconstitutionality" of provisional President Emile 
Jonassaint and his government. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

