<F P=100> Dominican Republic </F>
<F P=101> Haiti </F>
<H3> <TI>   Employers Organizations Condemn Provisional Government </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Employers Organizations Condemn Provisional Government </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   FL2305193094 Port-au-Prince Radio Metropole in French 1045 
GMT 23 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> FL2305193094 </F>
<F P=104>  Port-au-Prince Radio Metropole </F>
<F P=105>  French </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Two Haitian private sector employers organizations 
have condemned the appointment of Judge Emile Jonassaint as 
president of the Republic. The two organizations -- the Haitian 
Manufacturer's Association, or ADIH, and the Center for Free 
Enterprise and Democracy -- have demanded that the Governors 
Island agreement and New York pact be implemented and respected. 
  ADIH's executive council officially rejects the appointment 
of Judge Jonassaint and his de facto government and, until 
President Aristide appoints a new prime minister, recognizes as 
a legitimate government only the resigning government headed by 
Robert Malval. 
  In a press release, ADIH's executive council urges the other 
sectors of the national life to take a stand to obtain a return 
to constitutionality immediately and without delay. 
  As for the Center for Free Enterprise and Democracy, which 
has denounced the unconstitutionality of the Jonassaint 
government, it also denounced -- and I quote -- the immorality 
of Security Council Resolution No. 917 and the discrimination 
and hypocrisy of U.S. policy toward the Haitian refugees. 
  This center, which reminds the Army that under the 
Constitution, it has the duty to protect lives and property, 
also urges President Aristide to immediately appoint a new prime 
minister. 
  Finally, this center asks all the protagonists in the 
crisis, 
both civilian and military, to exhibit public-spiritedness and 
patriotism so as to spare the nation the shame of a military 
intervention. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

