<F P=100> Panama </F>
<H3> <TI>   Commission Safeguards Land Communication Progress </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Commission Safeguards Land Communication Progress </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA2405034194 Panama City EL SIGLO in Spanish 22 May 94 p 6 </F>
<F P=103> PA2405034194 </F>
<F P=104>  Panama City EL SIGLO </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By David Daniel Victoria] </F>
  [Text] The Colombian-Panamanian Neighborhood Commission 
agreed yesterday to send a note to Enrique Iglesias, president 
of the Inter-American Development Bank (IDB), creating a 
permanent organization to safeguard the progress of land 
communication between the two countries, an official source 
reported yesterday. 
  According to the source, the IDB committed itself to 
granting 
a nonreimbursable credit for $1.5 million for a study on the 
environmental impact of the construction of a highway linking 
Colombia and Panama. 
  During yesterday's meeting, it was agreed to create a 
banking 
and finance subcommission, and procedures were outlined to 
establish border markings. Also, an immigration agreement will 
be reached to provide documents for 15,000 Colombian immigrants 
who are in Panama illegally. 
  The Neighborhood Commission met for two days on Contadora 
Island for the last talks by Colombian delegates under the 
current government. 
  It was learned that the permanent commission for land 
communication, which will be made up of authorities from both 
countries, will define reference terms for the environmental 
impact study and explore possible sources of financing for the 
highway between Panama and Colombia. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

